name: 1,3-diphenyl-1-butanone
Reason: The basic units for the compound 1,3-diphenyl-1-butanone are benzene and butanone. The boiling point of benzene is approximately 80 degrees Celsius. Butanone, or methyl ethyl ketone, with a more substantial polar carbonyl group and two more carbon atoms than benzene, has a boiling point around 80 degrees Celsius, similar to benzene. The introduction of two phenyl groups to butanone will significantly increase the boiling point due to the increase in molecular weight, non-bonding interactions such as London dispersion forces, and pi-pi interactions between aromatic rings. Phenyl groups each add approximately 20 to 30 degrees Celsius due to these factors. However, the presence of the carbonyl group which can form dipole-dipole interactions and a slight increase in molecular rigidity may also raise the boiling point slightly. An additional 5 to 10 degrees Celsius for the carbonyl could be overlaid on the phenyl group effect.
